{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642619"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:42:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:42:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17957"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17957"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10671"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78859"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10671"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17957"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78859"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe foramen ovale is situated in the middle cranial fossa.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures emerges from the foramen ovale?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve","Maxillary division of the trigeminal nerve","Ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emandibular division of the trigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E exits the skull through the foramen ovale. This division is responsible for motor innervation to the muscles of mastication and sensory innervation to the lower face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOphthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This division exits through the superior orbital fissure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaxillary division of the trigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This division exits through the foramen rotundum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve exits through the stylomastoid foramen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve exits through the jugular foramen\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe foramen ovale is located in the sphenoid bone and is one of several foramina that allow cranial nerves to exit the skull.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve exits the skull through the foramen ovale.","The trigeminal nerve is the fifth cranial nerve and has three major divisions: ophthalmic, maxillary, and mandibular.","The foramen ovale is located in the sphenoid bone of the skull."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. Stat